Introduction¶

Thanksgiving is one of the most popular holidays in the United States. Every year, hundreds of millions gather with loved ones to celebrate. In this project, we're analyzing different traditions and ways people celebrate. Our goal is to analyze what factors affect how people celebrate. Doing so will help us to better understand the cultural and social dynamics of our fellow Americans.

To guide our analysis, we address the following questions:

  • Does one's demographical living area affect how far they will travel for thanksgiving?
  • Does household income differ across different ranges?
  • Among celebrators, do those who pray have as many common pie flavors present as those who do not pray?

Thanksgiving traditions are as diverse as the individuals who celebrate them, shaped by regional, cultural, and personal influences. By examining the connections between travel patterns, living environments, household income, and other traditions, we can uncover trends and correlations that reflect broader societal dynamics. Understanding these relationships is not only academically interesting but also valuable for businesses, policymakers, and community organizers seeking to connect with or support diverse populations across America. This analysis provides a lens through which we can appreciate the variations in how this cherished holiday is experienced across different communities.

Data Curation¶

Dataset:

https://github.com/fivethirtyeight/data/blob/master/thanksgiving-2015/thanksgiving-2015-poll-data.csv

In our goal to discover how Thanksgiving is celebrated across the U.S, we came across the above, a 2015 dataset containing the results of a Thanksgiving survey. This data is particularly interesting because it deals various topics related to the Thanksgiving holiday such as food, and we all love Thanksgiving food. After skimming through the data set, we saw a lot of variation in how people celebrate, so we decided to see the extent to which different households based on income, location, and average age celebrate Thanksgiving can vary. So to start, we first download the above CSV file from the Github page and upload it to the Google Colab directory for future use.

In this project, we are coding in Python using Google Colab to develop this project. The code below is some import statements for some of the main libraries we will be using throughout this tutorial.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Does one's demographical living area affect how far they will travel for thanksgiving?¶

Using Chi-square,

H0: There is no association between where people live and how far they travel for Thanksgiving.

Ha: There is an association between where people live now and how far they travel for Thanksgiving.

To help answer this question, we will create a subset of the data using the "RespondentID", "How would you describe where you live?", and "How far will you travel for Thanksgiving?" columns from the thanksgiving_df dataFrame. Next we drop any rows with the entry ‘NaN’ (this signifies missing values) to clean the subset before using it. Lastly, we display 14 rows to help visualize what the newly created subset is structured like.

By using the Pandas library we can create a contingency table for the "How would you describe where you live?" and "How far will you travel for Thanksgiving?" columns of the subset data frame. We are able to now find the P-value and plot the travel distances based on whether respondents live in urban, suburban, or rural areas.

In [ ]:
contingency_table = pd.crosstab(austin_df["How would you describe where you live?"], austin_df["How far will you travel for Thanksgiving?"])

Findings:

The p-value from the Chi-Square test is about 0.0568. With a significance level (alpha) of 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis at the 0.05 signifcance level since the P-value is greater than alpha. Therefore we can conclude there is no significant association between where people live and how far they travel for Thanksgiving.

Does household income differ across different ranges?¶

Ho: The mean income is the same across different age ranges¶

Ha: At least one age range has a different mean income from the others¶

Since we want to check if a person's age range has an impact on how much their household income is, we want to see if there is a correlation between the two categories. This is best done with an ANOVA test which we will conduct in the upcoming cells.

# This function will calculate a midpoint in a certain range which will help us gather numerical data for our test
def range_mdpt(income_range):
    # If they prefer not to say, we add a null value
    if 'Prefer' in income_range:
      return np.nan
    income_range = income_range.replace('$', '').replace(',', '').strip()

    # We set the lower bound if we have an unbounded range
    if 'and up' in income_range:
        lower_bound = int(income_range.split(' ')[0])
        upper_bound = lower_bound

    # Otherwise, we get the average of the upper and lower bound of the range
    else:
        income_range = income_range.split(' to ')
        lower_bound = int(income_range[0])
        upper_bound = int(income_range[1])

    return (lower_bound + upper_bound) / 2

df['household_income'] = df['How much total combined money did all members of your HOUSEHOLD earn last year?'].apply(range_mdpt)
df = df.dropna(subset=['Age', 'household_income'])

# We run the ANOVA test and get our p-value
income_by_age_range = [df['household_income'][df['Age'] == age_group] for age_group in df['Age'].unique()]
anova_result = stats.f_oneway(*income_by_age_range)
print(f"ANOVA Result: F-statistic = {anova_result.statistic}, p-value = {anova_result.pvalue}")

ANOVA Result: F-statistic = 35.51093763888391, p-value = 1.126909438442879e-21

This incredibly low p-value tells us that there is a significant impact between our two categories and allows us to reject the null hypothesis as our p-value is smaller than 0.5. Lets look at a graph distribution of our data to further this point.

In [ ]:
# We create a boxplot and stack each side by side for easy readable comparison
sns.boxplot(x='Age', y='household_income', data=df)
plt.title('Household Income Distribution by Age Range')
plt.xlabel('Age Range')
plt.ylabel('Household Income')
plt.show()

This graph further shows us that as the age ranges increase, the medians household incomes increase until they even out by the 45-59 and 60+ ranges. Overall, we can conclude that there is a significant correlation between the two categories.

Among celebrators, do those who pray have as many common pie flavors present as those who do not pray?¶

Ho: Prayers and non-prayers have the same number of common pie flavors present at their Thanksgiving.

Ha: Prayers and non-prayers have a different number of common pie flavors present at their Thanksgiving.

Since we are comparing two sample means, we will conduct a two sample t-test to prove or disprove our null hypothesis.

Primary Analysis¶

We would like to build a model using classification that will tell us if people that pray have as many common pie flavors as people that dont pray. Through this, we will be able to predict whether or not a person prays based on the presence of certain pie flavors.

#This will help balance our data by undersampling the majority: those who pray on Thanksgiving
#This is useful because it will reduce bias in our model
from imblearn.under_sampling import RandomUnderSampler

rus = RandomUnderSampler(random_state=42)
X_resampled, y_resampled = rus.fit_resample(X, y)
In [ ]:
#Train and evaluate the random forest classifier
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_resampled, y_resampled, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42, class_weight = 'balanced')
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

importances = clf.feature_importances_
print(importances)
#Get the names of the features
feature_names = X_train.columns

#Sort the importances in descending order
indices = np.argsort(importances)

#Clean the feature names
clean_feature_names = [name.split("- ")[-1] for name in feature_names]

#Plot the feature importances
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.title("Feature Importances")
plt.barh(range(len(indices)), importances[indices], align="center")
plt.yticks(range(len(indices)), [clean_feature_names[i] for i in indices])
plt.xlabel("Importance")
plt.show()

Insights and Conclusion¶

First let's recall the results of our machine learning model, and analyze its level of success.

In [ ]:
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

         0.0       0.57      0.79      0.66       105
         1.0       0.61      0.35      0.45        96

    accuracy                           0.58       201
   macro avg       0.59      0.57      0.56       201
weighted avg       0.59      0.58      0.56       201

Our model is 58% accurate, a moderate level of accuracy. This tells us that the model did decently well, and it correctly guesses more often than not. However, this model still has room for improvement. Looking specifically at instances of those who pray before or after their meal, we see the model struggles somewhat. Our recall value of 0.35 for our 1.0 class is a particular concern. This value shows that the model identified only 35% of those who actually responded that they pray. Our model is much better for predicting those who do not pray, as compared to predicting those who do.

Now let's consider the implications of our model's findings. By looking at the feature importances bar graph, the presence or non-presence of pumpkin pie was the most important feature in our model as about 15% of our model’s decision was affected by it. On the other hand, flavors like Buttermilk and Key Lime had the least influence of about 4.5% and 5.5% respectively. However, the range for the feature importances is roughly a little more than 10%. This shows that one feature was not unproportionally more significant than another.

Each respondent's diverse liking to different types of pie mirrors the diverse American population who celebrate Thanksgiving and their different traditions when celebrating this national holiday. So despite the fact that gatherings may or may involve prayers, we can all be thankful for our favorite types of pie and classification machine learning.
